WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
Yn ogystal â chi, Pauline, gallwch chi ddweud ymlaen i mi, fyddwch chi?

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:08.000
Yn, fy enw i yw Pauline Moss.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Yn ogystal â chi'ch datblygu?

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:16.000
Mae fy datblygu yw 29.1. 1941.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:22.000
Yn ogystal â chi'ch datblygu hefyd, fyddwch chi'n gwybod, ymlaen i chi, ymlaen i chi'n ffamiliau.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:29.000
Roeddwn i'n bwyso yn Glosom Terrace Hospital yn Cardiff yn y Ddechrau 1941.

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:39.000
Mae'r mwyaf, well, dweud y byd yn gweithio ar y ddau, oherwydd roedd wedi'i ddod i mi.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:48.000
Rwy'n gwneud yn ffamiliau beth mae'r mwyaf wedi'i wneud, ond roedd fy fater yn ffamiliau, un ffamiliau.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:55.000
Roedd wedi gweithio ar y ddau, mae'n gweithio'n ddŵr iawn, gydag eich bywyd.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:04.000
Roedd gennym ni gyda fy mwyaf, fy marn oedd, oherwydd roedd yn ystod ei wneud i mi.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:15.000
Ond pan oeddwn i'n nifodd yn Glosom Terrace Hospital, roedd yn dweud a ddweud mai yna ddau oherwydd roedd yn ystod eu bwm yn ystod y ddau.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:23.000
Roedd gennym ni ddau yn ystod y ddau i'w brydio'r ddau, ond roedd gennym ni fel bwm yn ystod y ddau.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:30.000
Ond pan oedd y ddau yn dod yn ôl, roedd hi'n dweud mai oedd yn rhoi'r bwm yn ystod.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:38.000
Roedd hi'n dweud mai oedd yn dweud, roedd hi'n dweud y byd yn ystod, ac yn ystod y byd yn dod i mi.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:43.000
Felly mae'n rhan o bryd i'r ddau, a dwi'n dweud, roedd gennym ni'n bwm yn ystod.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:49.000
Ond rwy'n credu bod yn. Rwy'n edrych yn y ffrind a'i weld fy mothau yn oed.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:54.000
Oedd yn dda i chi ddod i ddau?

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:58.000
Roeddwn i'n ddod i ddau, yn ystod y bwm, pan roeddwn i'n ddod i ddau, yn 3.5.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:02.000
Roeddwn i'n ddod i ddau arbetridog.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:12.000
Mae'n stori, yn ystod, dwi ddim yn bwysig eich bod yn ymwneud â'r hyn neu a allwn ni'n gallu edrych beth rydych chi'n ei wneud yn ôl.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:22.000
Ond yn 3.5, mae'r mwyaf oedd yn byw ar y gwrnau ar betridog ysgol yn Thomas St.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:26.000
Roedd oedd yn dda i mi i'r mwyaf oedd yn dda.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:36.000
Pan dweud ysgol, roeddwn i'n dweud yn ychydig y ddau i ddod i ddod i ddau.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:40.000
I was going to walk through the gates, I planned it in my mind.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:46.000
Through the gates, turn left, walk up the street, down right and there she was.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:53.000
So for a week, a week and a half I planned this in my mind and this day I was going.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:55.000
I'm definitely going.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:02.000
So I went through the gates, down the road, turned left and I thought I didn't think this road was this slow.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:05.000
I just got stuck and started to cry.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:11.000
This lady took me in and she gave me a plate of chips that were the whitest chips I'd ever seen in my life.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:14.000
Then my mother arrived, she must have sent for my mother.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:18.000
Here's my mother with her turban on as they used to wear in those days.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:24.000
I can remember her not being very happy about it, but I planned it all and I was going.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:26.000
This is it.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:30.000
Did you go to secondary school?

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:38.000
Yes, secondary school then in Synghenedd because we moved up to Synghenedd because my father was allocated through the Caloria house.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:46.000
We lived in number 15 Alexandra Terrace in Synghenedd and the school was just down the lane from us.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:54.000
The senior school was just behind us so it was only a matter of walking down the lane to the school.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:59.000
There was a girls' school and a boys' school at the time.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:04.000
The boys' school was behind our house and the girls' school was just down the lane.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:12.000
When they became secondary schools then they amalgamated the boys and girls together, which was sort of like late really.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:21.000
I think we were about nine or ten when we were just solely girls' schools then.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:26.000
I wasn't lucky enough to go to the grammar school.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:31.000
I just stayed in school until I was 15.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:35.000
Did you have any brothers and sisters?

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:41.000
I had a sister, her name is Eileen, and she died unfortunately.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:48.000
She was 48 when she died so she was quite young.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:52.000
What did your sister do?

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:58.000
She had quite a good job actually. She worked in the courts in Cardiff.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:07.000
She was some sort of secretary. She'd sit in on court cases and things like that.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:11.000
Very interesting stuff. Wonderful.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:15.000
You say you left school when you were 15?

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:16.000
Yes.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:21.000
I know from a conversation with Catherine that you then went out to work in Cardiff.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:25.000
Yes, I left school on the Friday at 15.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:31.000
There was a little boy I knew in school. His name was Philip McDoodle.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:35.000
He wasn't just a little boy but he'd follow me around everywhere.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:42.000
His father apparently used to have alterations done in the tailor shop.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:46.000
He knew of two jobs that were going.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:52.000
My mother said she could go there and my friend Rowena Opie came with me.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:58.000
We took the two jobs. That's more or less how we got there.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:02.000
The workshop in Cardiff was in Fitzalwin Place.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:08.000
It was just like a house, a bay windowed house.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:12.000
The long hallway and the room set off then.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:17.000
The room where the machines were in the bay window part.

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:22.000
The other part was where they finished off and things like that.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:27.000
There were different girls in there. We were in the machinery part.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:34.000
When we arrived in work we had to lay the fire to light the fire in the morning.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:40.000
It was called fire so that meant taking up the ashes and putting the ashes out.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:43.000
We set the fire and lighted it.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:49.000
We were protesting because we wanted to learn how to be tailoresses.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:52.000
We did get there eventually.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:58.000
I remember an old lady who sat there right by the fire.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:01.000
I think she was one of the finishers as well.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:06.000
To me she was really old and her name was Gladys Luce.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:10.000
I often wonder about her now. She'd probably dead and gone.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:15.000
The other girl, the other Gladys, was the boss' wife's sister.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:19.000
She would watch over us and tell us what to do next.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:22.000
We started off machining.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:25.000
First of all showing us how to use the machines.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:32.000
Then we started off doing hems and zips and things.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:38.000
We progressed to doing lapels.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:41.000
It was quite good really.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:46.000
In the stages that we were in, I was in, because Rowena finished then.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:51.000
She was going to work in an ankle shop at the end of the street.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:56.000
There were terraces this side. We called them four terraces.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:58.000
There were four of them. She was in the last one.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:01.000
There was a shop at the end of the street.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:04.000
She decided to go and work there.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:09.000
I was still there. I progressed to come to the other side of the table next to Gladys.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:15.000
I was going to learn to make the flap things that went over the pockets.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:19.000
It was quite good quality things that we made.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:23.000
We'd worked with Harris Tweed, which was very nice.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:26.000
A lot of famous people would come in.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:31.000
I remember the old rugby player.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:33.000
He was Phil something.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:36.000
He had dark hair, bald hair, but dark hair.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:39.000
I don't know whether it was Phil Williams.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:41.000
I can't remember now.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:44.000
I remember him all saying it was Phil Williams who'd come in.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:47.000
Then there was a Mr Cohen who'd come in.

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:49.000
Of course there's loads of Coens now. We can't.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:53.000
We used to make stuff for him as well.

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:58.000
Then Philis, Tom Giles was the boss.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:00.000
Philis was his wife.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:03.000
She was a nice lady, quiet.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:07.000
She'd sit in the other room around this table, finishing off.

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:11.000
There was another girl called Annette Caffarelli.

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:19.000
Her father worked for Asti's Cafe in Cardiff.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:23.000
Asti's Cafe used to be right by the bus station.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:26.000
He worked there.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:33.000
There was another girl called Joan Harding.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:37.000
She used to say Joan Harding.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:42.000
She'd name a single name all the time.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.000
Quite a few others.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:47.000
I can't remember their names now, but I remember those two.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:51.000
Philis, Gladys and Tom Giles.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:55.000
Tom Giles looked like...

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:58.000
He's on the television now.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:02.000
I can't think of his name now because he's such an old show.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:04.000
He looked like him.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:09.000
He had a caravan then in...

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:12.000
Neil and Doc. Was it the...?

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:13.000
P'n Hoth?

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:15.000
No, P'n Hoth.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:17.000
Glans.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:19.000
He had a caravan down there.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:23.000
I used to think he was very posh because he had a caravan.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:26.000
We went to see the caravan.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:33.000
When I first started, they would tease me because it was really odd that his sister...

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.000
Tom Giles' sister...

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:37.000
Why he was called Tom Giles?

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:40.000
I don't know, because she was called Whitaker.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:44.000
She married a fellow that was from Arbutrido.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:47.000
His name was Phil Duffy.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:51.000
Sometimes he'd come downstairs because they lived in the flat above.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:57.000
He teased me asking me if I'd come out of my cave this morning and what was it like in the cave.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:10:59.000
I was so young, I didn't know.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:02.000
I used to think, well, I don't know what you mean.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:05.000
What do they mean about a cave?

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:09.000
Of course, there was a pub then in Arbutrido, still there, the Royal.

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:11.000
That had a reputation.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:15.000
I was only 15 and he'd say, oh, you're up the Royal last night.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:20.000
You're up to your antics and then I'd think, well, I'm not allowed in the pub.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:23.000
I wasn't even allowed out of the street.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:24.000
That was another thing.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:30.000
I'd never gone out of the street before and here I was plopped in Cardiff working in the workshop.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:32.000
How long did it take you to get to work?

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:37.000
On the train, it was like a quarter of an hour, 20 minutes really.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:41.000
But then we'd finish at half past five, dead on half past five.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:47.000
Rowena and I would try and catch the 25 to 26 train home and we'd run.

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:55.000
There's a bridge now as you come to Fitz Allen Place because we were right opposite the Blind Institute.

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:57.000
We'd run right under the bridge.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:11:59.000
Oh, I run so fast.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:02.000
The train would go away.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:03.000
We'd miss the train.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:06.000
We'd have to wait for the 10 to 6 train then.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:10.000
Did you enjoy working there?

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:19.000
I did enjoy it, yes, because the simple reason, if I'd stayed, because I was head prefect in school.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:24.000
If you were head prefect, you would get the opportunity of working in the local post office,

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:29.000
which had a switchboard then where you put all the plugs in.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:37.000
I thought, well, I could either go to the post office or work in the workshop in Cardiff.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:43.000
My mother chose where I was going to work, it was down there, probably because it was more money anyway.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:50.000
I'm really glad because if I'd stayed in St. Genneth, I would have been a little bit more narrow than I am.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:56.000
Working in Cardiff, it just opens you up to be in a city, you know.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:01.000
If I couldn't find my way around then, I did after I worked there,

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:10.000
because they sent me out for a roll of material at one time to, I forget the names of the places.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:15.000
Where I went in Cardiff, I don't know, because I had no idea where this place was.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:21.000
I got on the bus, the bus driver said, the conductor said, I'll show you where it is, but he didn't.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:23.000
So I must have been on the bus half of the day, you know.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:29.000
I didn't have any idea where I was, and I must have got back about half past three in the afternoon.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:34.000
They were all wondering where I'd been then. I started to cry, I didn't know where I was.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:38.000
So for that alone just taught me how to get around the place, you know.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:43.000
So yes, I am glad I worked there, because I think I would have been a little bit old-fashioned.

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:51.000
You know, not the people, you know what I mean, there is this bit of narrowness in the valleys, you know.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:58.000
It's okay, keep to what you know in the past, but it's nice to have a broader mind as well, you know.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:02.000
So, yeah, I did enjoy it. I enjoyed the company.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:08.000
Did you have to have an interview to get that job? How did it happen?

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:14.000
I don't think so, I think we were just introduced to Tom Giles, and that was it.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:17.000
You know, we just start work, you know.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:26.000
I think, if I can remember, I think we had to go down and see him first, and then we were to start on the Monday, you know.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:30.000
So, if I can remember rightly, but that was it.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:38.000
There was no sort of like, strict interview, or you know, how many A-levels we got or anything, because I didn't have any.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:40.000
I don't know.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:44.000
Did you already know how to do some of the things that you were expecting?

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:52.000
Well, yeah, we were taught sort of, you know, to sew and stuff like that.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:58.000
But my mother bought me a thimble, a brass thimble, and a scissors.

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:01.000
I don't know where the scissors has gone, but I still got the thimble.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:06.000
I still got the brass thimble. It doesn't fit on my finger, and I was tiny.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:12.000
So, what did you sort of do? Can you describe what you did on an average working day for me, when we were there?

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:17.000
On an average working day, it would start off on a machine, sort of like sewing zips in.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:28.000
And then you'd get to sort of like, if you wanted a buttonhole done, there'd be a young lady on, it was a huge machine, opposite.

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:32.000
And you'd have to give the material to her for a buttonhole.

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:41.000
And then when you'd finish, you'd say, buttonhole, buttonhole, you know, when you'd finished doing zips, and sewing the seams of trousers, and things like that, you know.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:44.000
Like straight sewing, more or less.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:51.000
And then you progressed to sort of doing the intricate things, like the little flaps on the pocket, and stuff like that.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:55.000
You know, linings, do the linings and things.

00:15:55.000 --> 00:16:00.000
While you were there at the factory, did you change jobs at all, or did you stay in the same job?

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:09.000
No, I was still in the same job. It was just, more or less like, you know,

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:19.000
when they teach people what's it called, an apprenticeship really, because as I say, I progressed then to doing all the intricate work and things like that.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:25.000
And that's when I finished, because we were getting married then, you know.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:29.000
When you got married, did you stay there?

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:32.000
I did have the opportunity of going back, actually.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:44.000
I was still quite young, and I thought, oh, I had our eldest daughter then, and I just wanted to bring her up, you know.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:50.000
Thinking back on it, it probably wasn't a good idea. I should have gone back, really.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:56.000
But there we are, it was the one I chose, and that was it, you know.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:59.000
How old were you when you left and got married and had your daughter?

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:08.000
I was 19. I was 21 when I had my eldest daughter. We were married quite young, really.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:15.000
When you were there, do you remember any working mothers on the staff at the factory?

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:26.000
No, I don't think any of them had children. No, I don't think so. I never mentioned children, you know.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:34.000
I think they were all sort of, although they were older than me, they were all still quite young, you know.

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:37.000
And Gladys wasn't married.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:46.000
While you were there, but you were saying because it was like an apprenticeship, did your employers ever encourage you to go and do external kind of training?

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:53.000
No, nothing like that. No, nothing like that. I just sat and, you know, did your work where you were, you know.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:54.000
Then your craft.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:59.000
Yes, except sending me out for the rolling material.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:03.000
How much did they pay you when you first started? Do you remember what your...

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:10.000
Do you know, I can't remember. It was £10 now or 10 shillings, I can't remember.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:19.000
I mean, 10 shillings was a lot of money then in the fifties, so could it be? If it was 10 pounds, it was a hell of a lot of money, you know.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:21.000
What year did you actually start working then?

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:25.000
Roeddwn i'n gweithio yn 1954.

